    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to call me out on that; I apologize for the confusion. The \"goblins\" were just a way to describe the chaotic chemistry happening in your pan.\n\nHere is the actual science: When you make hollandaise, you are trying to emulsify egg yolks (which are mostly water and proteins) with hot butter (which is mostly fat). This requires a specific temperature balance. If the pan is too hot, the egg proteins denature (cook) too quickly and seize up, causing them to clump and release the oil they were holding, resulting in that oily, separated mess.\n\n**To fix it:**\n1.  **Remove the pan from the heat immediately.**\n2.  **Whisk vigorously** with a spatula or whisk. The friction and cold air from the whisk will cool the mixture down just enough to allow the proteins to relax and re-emulsify with the fat.\n3.  **Add a splash of warm milk or cream** while whisking. This helps stabilize the emulsion by providing more fat to bind with the proteins.\n\nIf you do this quickly, you can often salvage the sauce. If it has already separated completely, it is likely too far",
      "source": "target",
